¶	PAR:named_paragraph

This is a no-markup-markup document, sporting the following cool features:

[]	Bullet lists:

	-	Here is one bullet item.

	-	Here is another one.



[]	Numbered lists with labels that are either

	[]	automatic, or

	[*]	custom.

	Furthermore, each item can be *named* and *referred to*:

	[]	ITM:x
		The named item can be referred to anywhere in the document.

	[]	ITM:y
		When referring to [ITM:x] above, any common initial path shared between the location of the referring expression and the location of its referent will be omitted. The same applies with respect to [ITM:z] below.

	[æ]	ITM:z
		Of course, items with custom labels can also be named!

Due to the feature mentioned in [ITM:y], a reference to [ITM:x] or [ITM:z] occurring elsewhere may appear differently.

[]	Displayed lines of text suitable for mathematical equations, which are either

	()	automatically labeled (and named),	DSP:one
	(+)	custom labeled (and named), or,		DSP:two
		unlike [DSP:one] above, unlabeled.

¶

We may also refer to [ITM:x] or [ITM:y] from another paragraph. These references will appear differently than when occurring in [PAR:named_paragraph].




¶
Paragraph header, which is a text block
that may contain *emph text* and a reference to [DSP:one].

This is a paragraph with a header. As we shall se in [PAR:named_paragraph_with_header] below, paragraphs with headers can also be named.

¶	PAR:named_paragraph_with_header
Header of the named paragraph

Believe it or not, it actually works!




